[36:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of like each page and send that through the AI model as an image? In other words, what if we converted all of this into visual tokens instead and then just use like some optical recognition models to basically process the data. Now this'

[36:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a super technical scientific paper, but let me try to explain this in simple terms. Here is their proposed architecture. Basically, instead of inputting text, you would take a screenshot of whatever you want to'

[37:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'input. So, it\'s basically an image and then it would break this down into chunks at a time like this. And then these chunks will be fed through this deep encoder component. This consists of this SAM or segment anything model. And'

[37:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is in charge of basically focusing on small local areas of the image to capture fine details. And then after capturing the fine details, the data is then downsampled or basically compressed'

[37:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '16 times through this convolutional neural network. And then afterwards we are left with these compressed vision tokens which then get fed through this clip component which is focused on'

[37:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understanding the context and relationships across the entire image. All right. So this is also called global attention. So again, SAM is focused on local attention or capturing the fine details of the image whereas clip is'

[37:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'focused on global attention or trying to understand the context and relationships between everything in the image. And then after this deep encoder component, the data is then fed through this very tiny deepseek 3 billion parameter model.'

[38:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is a mixture of experts model with only 570 million active parameters. And this is basically used to decode these vision tokens back into text. So here'

[38:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
